# Understanding WAL mode

SQLite's *write-ahead log* changes the concurrency story completely. Instead of writers blocking readers, the WAL lets readers keep a stable snapshot while a single writer appends.

## The basics

Enable it with a pragma:

```
PRAGMA journal_mode = WAL;
PRAGMA synchronous = NORMAL;
-- and always set a busy timeout
PRAGMA busy_timeout = 5000;
```

Note that `<checkpoint>` behavior depends on the [documentation](https://sqlite.org/wal.html).

> A single writer matches SQLite's actual concurrency model.

![WAL architecture diagram](https://example.com/images/wal-diagram.png)

Readers see the snapshot; the writer appends.

## Checklist

*   WAL mode on
*   busy\_timeout set
*   one writer thread
    *   channel-fed
    *   transactional

| Mode   | Readers during write |
| ------ | -------------------- |
| DELETE | blocked              |
| WAL    | concurrent           |
